</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Quadratic Equations</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>A quadratic equation has the general form,</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">ax<SUP>2</SUP>  + bx + c = 0</P>

<P>where a, b and c are real numbers, a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#185;</FONT>
 0.   Notice the power of the variable in a quadratic equation is 2.</P>

<P>Examples of quadratic equations would be</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">6x<SUP>2 </SUP>+ 3x + 1 = 0</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">½ p<SUP>2</SUP> – p  =  ¼</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">3.14m<SUP>2</SUP> = 6.28</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<br>
<P>Study Lesson 1-30 <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 30 a~?">section a</a> for an introduction to quadratic equations and their solution.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Solving Quadratic Equations by Factorisation</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>Quadratic equations can be easily solved if the expression ax<SUP>2</SUP> + bx + c can be factorised.</P> 

<B><P>Example </P></B>
<P>The temperature T (<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
C) at which water boils is related to the elevation h (in metres above sea level) by the quadratic relationship</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">1000(100 – T) + 580(100 – T)<SUP>2</SUP> = h</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>At what temperature will water boil at sea level ?</P>
<br>
<P><B>Solution</P>
</B>
<P>At sea level h =0.</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 1000(100 – T) + 580(100 – T)<SUP>2</SUP> = 0</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
(100 - T)(1000 + 580(100 – T)) = 0&#9; (taking out a factor of (100 – T))</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
(100 – T) = 0 or (1000 + 580(100 – T)) = 0</P>
<br>
<P><B>therefore</B></P>

<P>100 – T = 0
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 -T = -100
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
<B>T =100</B>

<P><B>or</B></P>

<P>1000 + 580(100 – T) =0
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
1000 + 58000 – 580T = 0
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 59000 – 580T = 0</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 580T = 59000
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 T = 59000/580
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 <B>T = 101.7 (to 1 dp)</B></P>

<P>hence, at sea level(as expected) water will boil at 100<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
C.</P>

<br>
<P>If you feel that you need help with factorising quadratic expressions then work through the Learning Plan <B>"Factorisation"</B> in <B>Test 3 Revision</B>.</P>

